\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Cointegrated Time Seires
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 time series process, and there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\beta}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\beta}^{\prime}\bm{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

, the variables are said to be cointegrated.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is called a cointegrating vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The question of whether a genuine relationship exists between a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 time series can be posed as the question: are the variables cointegrated?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
It is possible that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is not unique and there are several linearly independent vectors, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\beta}_{1},\cdots,\bm{\beta}_{s}$
\end_inset

, each of which is a cointegrating vector for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The space spanned by these vectors is called the cointegrating space for
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the cointegrating rank of the variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The VECM Framework
\end_layout

